	in <a href="https://www.centosblog.com/categories/administration/" title="View all posts in Administration">Administration</a>, <a href="https://www.centosblog.com/categories/centos-6/" title="View all posts in CentOS 6">CentOS 6</a>, <a href="https://www.centosblog.com/categories/general/" title="View all posts in General">General</a>, <a href="https://www.centosblog.com/categories/networking/" title="View all posts in Networking">Networking</a>, <a href="https://www.centosblog.com/categories/quick-tips/" title="View all posts in Quick Tips">Quick Tips</a></span>
	
		<span class="date-post">Feb, 16 2014</span>
	
		<span class="com-post">
		<a href="https://www.centosblog.com/script-update-centos-linux-servers-hostname/#comments">5 Comments</a>
	</span>
	
			</div><!-- .entry-meta -->
	</header><!-- .entry-header -->
				
	<div class="entry-content">
		<p>Want to quickly change the hostname of your server? Use this simple script:</p>
<pre class="brush: bash; title: ; notranslate" title="">
#!/usr/bin/env bash

OLD_HOSTNAME=&quot;$( hostname )&quot;
NEW_HOSTNAME=&quot;$1&quot;

if [ -z &quot;$NEW_HOSTNAME&quot; ]; then
 echo -n &quot;Please enter new hostname: &quot;
 read NEW_HOSTNAME &lt; /dev/tty
fi

if [ -z &quot;$NEW_HOSTNAME&quot; ]; then
 echo &quot;Error: no hostname entered. Exiting.&quot;
 exit 1
fi

echo &quot;Changing hostname from $OLD_HOSTNAME to $NEW_HOSTNAME...&quot;

hostname &quot;$NEW_HOSTNAME&quot;

sed -i &quot;s/HOSTNAME=.*/HOSTNAME=$NEW_HOSTNAME/g&quot; /etc/sysconfig/network

if [ -n &quot;$( grep &quot;$OLD_HOSTNAME&quot; /etc/hosts )&quot; ]; then
 sed -i &quot;s/$OLD_HOSTNAME/$NEW_HOSTNAME/g&quot; /etc/hosts
else
 echo -e &quot;$( hostname -I | awk '{ print $1 }' )\t$NEW_HOSTNAME&quot; &gt;&gt; /etc/hosts
fi

echo &quot;Done.&quot;
</pre>

